[
    {
        "content": "<p>Yesterday I PRed a few results about the variance <code>Var[X ; μ]</code> in <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/28248\">#28248</a>. Yesterday is also the day I learned that we had a linter for spaces before a semicolon: <code> ;</code> <span aria-label=\"neutral\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f610\" role=\"img\" title=\"neutral\">:neutral:</span> What should I do?</p>",
        "id": 533913210,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1754978700
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Personnally I have been writing <code>Var[X; mu]</code>.</p>",
        "id": 533916499,
        "sender_full_name": "Etienne Marion",
        "timestamp": 1754980655
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But isn't <code>;</code> supposed to be an infix?</p>",
        "id": 533916584,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1754980693
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Not having been educated in France, I find spaces before punctuation very jarring.</p>",
        "id": 533916863,
        "sender_full_name": "Damiano Testa",
        "timestamp": 1754980847
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Looking at the variance file, it’s all written without a space, and the notation is defined without a space too.</p>",
        "id": 533917506,
        "sender_full_name": "Etienne Marion",
        "timestamp": 1754981171
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But isn't it supposed to mimic the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>∼</mo><mi>μ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X \\sim μ</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∼</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">μ</span></span></span></span> notation?</p>",
        "id": 533917565,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1754981210
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You don't write <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mtext> ⁣</mtext><mtext> ⁣</mtext><mo>∼</mo><mi>μ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X\\!\\!\\sim μ</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:-0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:-0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∼</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">μ</span></span></span></span>, I presume.</p>",
        "id": 533917629,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1754981238
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Indeed I don't write that, but that's not how I interpret the notation. To me <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>∼</mo><mi>μ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X \\sim \\mu</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∼</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">μ</span></span></span></span> means <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> has law <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>μ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mu</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">μ</span></span></span></span> under some probability measure on the domain of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>, while in <code>Var[X; μ]</code>, <code>μ</code> is the measure on the domain of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>, not its law. So it's more like \"the variance of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> with respect to the measure <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>μ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mu</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">μ</span></span></span></span>\", which I would write I think <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></mrow><mi>μ</mi></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{Var}_{\\mu}[X]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0361em;vertical-align:-0.2861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Var</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1514em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">μ</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2861em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 533918449,
        "sender_full_name": "Etienne Marion",
        "timestamp": 1754981685
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If it's the fact that we're using punctuation as an infix that's jarring, maybe we should find a different symbol?</p>",
        "id": 533918485,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1754981707
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><code>Var[X; mu]</code> seems not-at-all jarring to me?</p>",
        "id": 533918873,
        "sender_full_name": "Kim Morrison",
        "timestamp": 1754981930
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, but in PFR there's suddenly <code>dk[κ ; μ # η ; ν]</code> and then it's not clear <code>dk[κ; μ # η; ν]</code> is the right choice</p>",
        "id": 533919558,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1754982269
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Sorry, I didn't imagine this would be at all polemical</p>",
        "id": 533919632,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1754982306
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't think <code>dk[κ; μ # η; ν]</code>is a problem either.</p>",
        "id": 533922961,
        "sender_full_name": "Sébastien Gouëzel",
        "timestamp": 1754983803
    }
]